  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">William Lloyd Garrison praises Fanny Garrison Villard&apos;s diligence and punctuality as a correspondent. Frank &quot;has a large bundle of your letters carefully preserved, which darling Helen may some day peruse with interest and delight.&quot; William L. Garrison wishes he could have been there when the grandchildren received their Christmas presents. William L. Garrison writes: &quot;It is too late to suggest to your mother not to send you or the children any boots or shoes; for they were forwarded last month, and doubtless, by this time, are in your possession.&quot; Garrison says: &quot;Until yesterday, the new year has been the mildest for forty years, not a trace of ice or snow to be found; but a heavy snow-storm came down upon us all day yesterday, ...&quot;</subfield>
